  "prompt": "What happens to a photon after it hits the retina of my eye?",
  "response": "When a photon of light hits the retina of your eye, several key processes occur that lead to the perception of light. Here\u2019s a step-by-step overview of what happens:\n\n1. **Absorption by Photoreceptors**: The retina contains specialized cells called photoreceptors, which include rods and cones. These cells contain light-sensitive proteins called photopigments. When a photon strikes a photoreceptor, it is absorbed by these photopigments (such as rhodopsin in rods and photopsins in cones).\n\n2. **Isomerization**: The absorption of the photon causes a change in the structure of the photopigment, a process known as isomerization. For example, in the case of rhodopsin, the retinal molecule changes from a bent form (11-cis-retinal) to a straight form (all-trans-retinal).\n\n3. **Activation of Phototransduction Cascade**: This structural change triggers a biochemical cascade called the phototransduction pathway. This pathway involves a series of molecular events, including the activation of a protein called transducin, which in turn activates phosphodiesterase (PDE). \n\n4. **Reduction of cGMP Levels**: Activated PDE breaks down cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP), a secondary messenger that keeps ion channels open in the photoreceptor membrane. As cGMP levels decrease, these ion channels close.\n\n5. **Hyperpolarization of the Photoreceptor**: The closing of ion channels leads to hyperpolarization of the photoreceptor cell, meaning its interior becomes more negatively charged. This change in membrane potential alters the release of neurotransmitters (like glutamate) at the synapse with bipolar cells.\n\n6. **Signal Transmission**: The change in neurotransmitter release affects bipolar cells, which transmit the signal to ganglion cells in the retina. Depending on the type of bipolar cell, the response can either be excitatory or inhibitory.\n\n7. **Action Potentials to the Brain**: The ganglion cells generate action potentials that travel along their axons, forming the optic nerve. This nerve transmits visual information from the retina to the brain.\n\n8. **Processing in the Brain**: The visual information is sent to various areas of the brain, particularly the primary visual cortex, where it is processed and interpreted, ultimately allowing you to perceive the light and form images.\n\nIn summary, a photon hitting the retina initiates a complex series of biochemical and electrical events that culminate in the perception of light and visual information by the brain.",
